Less than a week after President Uhuru Kenyatta and Mombasa Governor Hassan Joho clashed over the Jubilee administration&rsquo;s development record at the Coast, State House yesterday listed projects the state has initiated .State House spokesman Manoah Esipisu underscored the billions of shillings in massive development projects invested in the six Coast counties since the Jubilee administration came into power in 2013.He said the development credentials of the Jubilee administration are &ldquo;clear for everyone to see, and no amount of juvenile tantrums from any quarters would negate the improved services&rdquo;.Esipisu said Uhuru&rsquo;s government has pumped billions of shillings into security, healthcare, roads, markets, electricity and schools.He said security has received 177 vehicles under the government&rsquo;s innovative leasing programme, more than 1,000 police officers, and a satellite security surveillance system that has improved security in Mombasa.&ldquo;Improved security, better roads, a better performing port, in general better lives for the people of this region. That is what this administration promised, and that&rsquo;s what it is delivering,&rdquo; Esipisu said.Among the projects, he said are water in Kwale, Mombasa, Taita Taveta and Tana River counties.&ldquo;In Mombasa county, the Coast General Hospital has been equipped with modern equipment at Sh460 million, while the Likoni Level 4 Hospital has Sh430 million equipment,&rdquo; Esipisu said.He said in Kilifi, the Malindi Level 5 Hospital was equipped at the cost of Sh430 million.In Kwale county, Msambweni Level 5 Hospital was equipped at the cost of Sh460 million. In Lamu county, Esipisu said Lamu Level 5 Hospital was supplied with modern medical equipment and facilities worth Sh430 million.In addition, Sh200 million was given to the Lamu Level 5 Hospital as a special grant to upgrade it.Faza Level 4 Hospital was also equipped with medical equipment at a cost of Sh380 million.